          "body": "Verses 7-8 give the first concrete instance of YHWH's condescension: He raises the poor (*dal*) from the dust and lifts the needy (*evyon*) from the ash heap — to sit with princes, with the princes of His people. The ash heap (*ashpot*) is not merely a figure of speech. In the ancient Near East it was the literal refuse dump outside the city gate, where the destitute sat, scavenged, and begged — where Job sat in his devastation (Job 2:8). To be lifted from there to the princes' table is not incremental social improvement; it is categorical reversal. The vocabulary is unmistakably Hanna-sonic. Hannah's song in 1 Samuel 2:7-8 uses virtually identical imagery: 'He raises the poor from the dust, He lifts the needy from the ash heap, to make them sit with nobles and inherit a seat of honor.' Psalm 113 is either quoting Hannah's song or drawing from a shared theological tradition — both assert that what YHWH did for one barren woman in Shiloh expresses His permanent character. The reversal is not anomalous; it is characteristic."
