          "title": "Psalm 113 and the incarnation — Hallel at the Last Supper",
          "body": "Matthew 26:30 and Mark 14:26 record that Jesus and His disciples 'sang a hymn' before going out to the Mount of Olives. Jewish Passover practice fixed Psalms 113-114 as the pre-meal Hallel and 115-118 as the post-meal Hallel. If so, the psalm Jesus sang — within hours of Gethsemane, the cross, and the tomb — was the very psalm that describes the God who 'humbles Himself to behold' (113:6) and who raises the poor from the dust (113:7). The Philippians 2 hymn uses cognate language: the Son 'emptied Himself, taking the form of a bond-servant' and 'humbled Himself by becoming obedient to the point of death' (*etapeinōsen heauton*) — the same voluntary condescension Psalm 113:6 announces in *shaphel*. The incarnation is not a departure from YHWH's character; it is its definitive enactment. The God who stooped to see the ash heap stepped into it. The psalmist's Hallelujah becomes, in retrospect, the church's Easter doxology — praise for the God who raised the ultimate poor man, the one buried in the ultimate dust, and seated Him at the right hand of Majesty on high (Hebrews 1:3)."
